{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17488478","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17488478"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:43:24+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:43:24+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"456"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"456","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/456"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.19,0.51,0.04,0.02,0.24]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"456"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"43502"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"456","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/456"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"456"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"28503"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"410"},{"type":"tags","id":"1140"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4977"},{"type":"tags","id":"11626"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3493"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3632"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40709"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44463"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"43502","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/43502"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 69-year-old woman presents to her General Practitioner with a painless lesion on her lower lip (Image), which first appeared one month ago. This has gradually grown, with no other changes in appearance, associated itchiness or pain of the lesion. She has a medical history of osteoarthritis and gets regular cold sores. Her medications include paracetamol, ibuprofen, and docosanol cream PRN. She has a 15 pack-year smoking history and quit five years ago. She drinks three glasses of red wine each evening and uses no recreational drugs.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely predisposing cause?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Herpes simplex","Sun exposure","Recurrent trauma","Drug allergy","Smoking"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis is a squamous cell carcinoma (SCC) of the vermillion. The most likely predisposing cause is UV exposure, specifically - cumulative \u003Cstrong\u003Esun exposure\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHerpes simplex\u003C/strong\u003E is not associated with SCC, but does cause oral ulcers which tend to affect the lips, tongue, gums, inner cheeks and roof of the mouth. Chronic inflammation associated with ulcers can be a risk factor.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERecurrent trauma\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Esmoking tobacco\u003C/strong\u003E are associated with SCC, but are less significant risk factors compared to sun exposure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFixed drug reactions caused by \u003Cstrong\u003Edrug allergy\u003C/strong\u003E can cause lip and tongue lesions, but are usually a red patch or plaque and would not last for several months.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Squamous cell carcinoma most often affect sun exposed areas including the lips.","The greatest risk factor for SCC is cumulative sun exposure."],"references":["Parekh V, Seykora JT. Cutaneous Squamous Cell Carcinoma. Clin Lab Med. 2017;37(3):503-525. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/28802498/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"28503"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"456"}},"stemMedia":{